{"completedAt":"2026-03-14T20:15:40.407Z","ok":true,"requestId":"orchestrate_testing_1773519340373_4","result":{"plan":{"objective":"Validate newly implemented feature behavior end-to-end","rationale":"To ensure that the new feature works correctly in the local development environment, we will automate the testing process using Playwright. This will help identify any issues before deployment.","app_bootstrap":{"required":true,"reason":"The application needs to be started to perform end-to-end testing.","workspace":"C:\\Users\\William\\Desktop\\Projects\\Genai_2026","files":[],"install_command":"npm install","start_command":"npm start","startup_timeout_ms":30000},"steps":[{"action":"goto","target":"http://127.0.0.1:8093"},{"action":"wait","target":10000},{"action":"assertVisible","target":"text=Jungle"},{"action":"screenshot","target":"screenshot.png"}],"assertions":["The application should load without errors.","The 'Jungle' text should be visible on the page."],"success_criteria":["The application starts successfully.","The expected elements are visible on the page.","The final screenshot is captured without errors."]},"execution":{"status":"fail","summary":"locator.waitFor: Timeout 10000ms exceeded.\nCall log:\n\u001b[2m  - waiting for locator('text=Jungle').first() to be visible\u001b[22m\n","steps":[],"video_path":"C:\\Users\\William\\Desktop\\Projects\\Genai_2026\\db\\langflow_agentic_runs\\run_18944_1773519371761\\3b1d9cb7e8c7826c1b83404d1e5f925c.webm","artifacts":["C:\\Users\\William\\Desktop\\Projects\\Genai_2026\\db\\langflow_agentic_runs\\run_18944_1773519371761\\3b1d9cb7e8c7826c1b83404d1e5f925c.webm","C:\\Users\\William\\Desktop\\Projects\\Genai_2026\\db\\langflow_agentic_runs\\run_18944_1773519371761\\final_1773519392153.png","C:\\Users\\William\\Desktop\\Projects\\Genai_2026\\db\\langflow_agentic_runs\\run_18944_1773519371761\\playwright_executor.generated.js","C:\\Users\\William\\Desktop\\Projects\\Genai_2026\\db\\langflow_agentic_runs\\run_18944_1773519371761\\request_parser.json"],"generated_code_path":"C:\\Users\\William\\Desktop\\Projects\\Genai_2026\\db\\langflow_agentic_runs\\run_18944_1773519371761\\playwright_executor.generated.js","parser_path":"C:\\Users\\William\\Desktop\\Projects\\Genai_2026\\db\\langflow_agentic_runs\\run_18944_1773519371761\\request_parser.json","stdout":"{\"status\":\"fail\",\"summary\":\"locator.waitFor: Timeout 10000ms exceeded.\\nCall log:\\n\\u001b[2m  - waiting for locator('text=Jungle').first() to be visible\\u001b[22m\\n\",\"steps\":[],\"video_path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\William\\\\Desktop\\\\Projects\\\\Genai_2026\\\\db\\\\langflow_agentic_runs\\\\run_18944_1773519371761\\\\3b1d9cb7e8c7826c1b83404d1e5f925c.webm\",\"artifacts\":[\"C:\\\\Users\\\\William\\\\Desktop\\\\Projects\\\\Genai_2026\\\\db\\\\langflow_agentic_runs\\\\run_18944_1773519371761\\\\3b1d9cb7e8c7826c1b83404d1e5f925c.webm\",\"C:\\\\Users\\\\William\\\\Desktop\\\\Projects\\\\Genai_2026\\\\db\\\\langflow_agentic_runs\\\\run_18944_1773519371761\\\\final_1773519392153.png\",\"C:\\\\Users\\\\William\\\\Desktop\\\\Projects\\\\Genai_2026\\\\db\\\\langflow_agentic_runs\\\\run_18944_1773519371761\\\\playwright_executor.generated.js\",\"C:\\\\Users\\\\William\\\\Desktop\\\\Projects\\\\Genai_2026\\\\db\\\\langflow_agentic_runs\\\\run_18944_1773519371761\\\\request_parser.json\"]}","stderr":"","app_runtime":{"status":"already_running","target_url":"http://127.0.0.1:8093","ready":true,"started_by_orchestrator":false,"workspace":"C:\\Users\\William\\Desktop\\Projects\\Genai_2026","start_command":"","install_command":"","log_path":null,"pid":null,"error_message":""}},"critique":{"verdict":"fail","overall_severity":10,"summary":"The application fundamentally fails as a physics visualizer. The core animation logic implements a linear motion profile instead of the required sinusoidal Simple Harmonic Motion, resulting in a physically impossible and robotic movement. This is compounded by severe animation judder due to a low-frequency update loop. Critically, the visual representation of the mass's motion directly contradicts the numerical data for kinetic and potential energy, completely undermining the tool's purpose and credibility.","defects":[{"id":"incorrect_physics_model","severity_0_10":10,"description":"The mass moves with a constant linear velocity, failing to slow down as it approaches the endpoints and speed up as it passes through equilibrium. This is fundamentally incorrect for a spring-mass system, which should exhibit sinusoidal velocity and acceleration based on Hooke's Law. The current motion feels weightless and lacks any sense of inertia or dynamic force.","evidence":"Throughout the video, the red mass travels back and forth at a visually constant speed. Its direction change at the endpoints is instantaneous.","recommendation":"Replace the current position update logic with a proper physics integration. At each time step (`dt`), calculate force (`F = -kx`), then acceleration (`a = F/m`), then update velocity (`v += a * dt`), and finally update position (`x += v * dt`). Using a numerical integrator like Velocity Verlet will produce the correct sinusoidal motion."},{"id":"data_visualization_mismatch","severity_0_10":10,"description":"The numerical readouts for Kinetic Energy (KE) and Potential Energy (PE) correctly show a sinusoidal transfer of energy consistent with proper SHM. However, the visual animation of the mass moves at a constant speed, which is a completely different and physically incorrect motion model. The UI presents two conflicting sources of information, breaking the user's trust.","evidence":"The numerical displays for KE and PE cycle smoothly between their maximum and minimum values, while the red mass on screen moves at a constant velocity.","recommendation":"Establish a single source of truth for the system's state. The same `position` and `velocity` variables calculated in the core physics loop must be used to both (1) render the position of the mass on screen and (2) calculate the KE (`0.5*m*v^2`) and PE (`0.5*k*x^2`) for the numerical display."},{"id":"instantaneous_velocity_inversion","severity_0_10":9,"description":"At the moment the mass reaches its maximum displacement, its velocity reverses instantaneously. An object with mass cannot change velocity without acceleration over time; this behavior requires infinite force and is physically impossible. This abrupt 'snap' is a jarring artifact that removes the characteristic 'hang time' of an oscillating object.","evidence":"At both the left and right turning points, the mass does not decelerate to a stop. It maintains full speed until the last frame and appears in the next frame moving at full speed in the opposite direction.","recommendation":"This issue is a direct symptom of the incorrect physics model. Implementing the recommended force-based physics simulation will inherently solve this. The restoring force will naturally cause the mass to decelerate smoothly to a velocity of zero at the endpoints before accelerating it in the opposite direction."},{"id":"animation_judder","severity_0_10":8,"description":"The motion of the mass is not smooth, exhibiting severe judder. The mass visibly 'jumps' or 'teleports' in discrete steps rather than traveling smoothly. This indicates that the animation is running at a very low and/or inconsistent frame rate, likely due to an improper update loop (e.g., slow `setInterval`). This breaks the illusion of continuous motion and degrades readability.","evidence":"The red mass does not move smoothly across the screen. Its movement is a series of discrete, visible jumps from one position to the next.","recommendation":"Decouple the physics simulation from the rendering loop. Use `requestAnimationFrame()` for all visual updates to synchronize drawing with the monitor's refresh rate, which will eliminate judder. The physics calculations should be run on a separate, fixed time step for stability and determinism."}],"strengths":[],"recommendations":["Overhaul the core logic to use a proper physics-based simulation (e.g., Velocity Verlet integrator) derived from Hooke's Law to accurately model Simple Harmonic Motion.","Refactor the rendering loop to use `requestAnimationFrame()` to ensure smooth, judder-free animation synchronized with the display's refresh rate.","Unify the application's state management so that the visual animation and the numerical data displays are both driven by the same underlying physics variables, ensuring consistency."],"source":"gemini_chain_video","critic_chain":{"video":{"video_input_used":true,"video_reason":"inline_video_attached","video_bytes":749412},"detailed_text":"Of course. As a strict animation and physics QA critic, I have analyzed the provided video of your \"SHM Spring Visualizer.\" The application's subtitle, \"Intentionally poor physics and UX,\" is accurate. Below is a comprehensive, technical critique of the animation and interaction behaviors.\n\n---\n\n### 1) Linear Motion Profile & Non-Sinusoidal Velocity\n**What happens**\nThe red mass moves back and forth with a visually constant velocity. It does not slow down as it approaches the endpoints, nor does it speed up as it passes through the central equilibrium point.\n\n**Why it looks wrong**\nThis motion is fundamentally incorrect for a spring-mass system. The physics of Simple Harmonic Motion (SHM) are governed by Hooke's Law (`F = -kx`), where the restoring force is proportional to the displacement (`x`). This dictates that acceleration is maximum at the endpoints (where the force is greatest) and zero at the equilibrium point. Consequently, the velocity profile must be sinusoidal (a cosine function if released from rest at maximum displacement), being zero at the endpoints and maximum at the center. The current implementation displays a \"triangle wave\" for position over time, which corresponds to a \"square wave\" for velocity. This feels robotic, weightless, and lacks any sense of inertia or dynamic force.\n\n**Fix**\nThe animation logic must be driven by a proper physics integration. Instead of updating position with a constant velocity (`x += v * dt`), you must calculate the state variables at each time step (`dt`).\n1.  Calculate force: `force = -k * position` (where `k` is the spring constant).\n2.  Calculate acceleration: `acceleration = force / mass`.\n3.  Update velocity: `velocity += acceleration * dt`.\n4.  Update position: `position += velocity * dt`.\nUsing a numerical integrator like Velocity Verlet or RK4 will yield a more stable and accurate simulation that produces the correct sinusoidal motion.\n\n### 2) Low-Frequency Update & Motion Judder\n**What happens**\nThe red mass does not travel smoothly. Instead, it visibly \"jumps\" or \"teleports\" in discrete steps along its path. The animation appears to be running at a very low and inconsistent frame rate.\n\n**Why it looks wrong**\nThis is a classic case of **frame-rate clipping** or judder, which severely degrades motion readability. The illusion of continuous motion is broken because the positional updates are too infrequent for the human eye to perceive as smooth. This suggests the animation loop is not synchronized with the display's refresh rate, likely relying on a slow `setInterval()` or `setTimeout()`. The large, discrete jumps in position indicate that the time delta (`dt`) between updates is too large.\n\n**Fix**\nDecouple the physics simulation loop from the rendering loop and use `requestAnimationFrame()` for all visual updates.\n1.  **Rendering:** The `requestAnimationFrame()` callback should be responsible only for drawing the state of the system (the ball's position, the spring's stretch) on the screen. This ensures rendering is synchronized with the monitor's refresh rate (typically 60Hz), eliminating judder.\n2.  **Physics:** Run the physics calculations on a separate, fixed time step (e.g., using `setInterval(physicsUpdate, 10)` for a 100Hz update rate). This ensures the simulation is deterministic and stable, regardless of rendering performance. For ultimate smoothness, the rendering loop can interpolate the object's position between the last two physics states.\n\n### 3) Instantaneous Velocity Inversion at Endpoints\n**What happens**\nWhen the mass reaches its maximum displacement (either fully stretched or fully compressed), its direction of motion reverses instantaneously. There is no visible deceleration to a stop or subsequent acceleration in the new direction.\n\n**Why it looks wrong**\nThis is a form of **corner glitching** applied to a 1D motion path. An object with mass cannot change its velocity instantaneously, as this would require infinite acceleration and thus an infinite force, violating Newton's laws of motion. This abrupt \"snap\" at the turning points is the most jarring visual artifact of the linear motion model. It completely removes the characteristic \"hang time\" where the object momentarily pauses before changing direction, which is crucial for believable physics.\n\n**Fix**\nThis issue is a direct symptom of the flawed model described in Problem #1. Implementing a proper force-based physics simulation will inherently solve this. As the mass approaches an endpoint, the restoring force will cause it to decelerate smoothly to a velocity of zero. The force will then continue to act on the mass, accelerating it smoothly in the opposite direction.\n\n### 4) Data-Visualization Mismatch\n**What happens**\nThe numerical readouts for Kinetic Energy (KE) and Potential Energy (PE) correctly show a sinusoidal transfer of energy, consistent with proper SHM. The PE is maximum when KE is zero (at the endpoints), and vice-versa (at the equilibrium point). However, the visual animation of the mass does not reflect this; it moves at a constant speed.\n\n**Why it looks wrong**\nThe UI presents two conflicting sources of information. The data *tells* the user that the system is behaving correctly according to SHM principles, but the animation *shows* a completely different, physically incorrect motion. This breaks the user's trust in the simulation. It implies that either the animation logic is disconnected from the physics engine driving the data, or the data itself is being \"faked\" with a simple sine/cosine function rather than being derived from the system's actual state.\n\n**Fix**\nEnsure a single source of truth for the system's state. The same `position` and `velocity` variables calculated in the physics loop (as per the fix for Problem #1) must be used for two purposes:\n1.  To calculate the KE (`0.5 * m * v^2`) and PE (`0.5 * k * x^2`) for the numerical display.\n2.  To directly determine the pixel coordinates of the red mass on the screen for rendering.\nThis will guarantee that the visual representation is a perfect match for the underlying data.","severity":{"overall_severity":10,"severity_reasoning":"The application fails on every fundamental level. The core physics model is incorrect (linear instead of sinusoidal), the animation rendering is severely degraded by low-frequency updates causing judder, and the visual representation directly contradicts the numerical data, completely undermining the purpose of the visualizer.","top_risks":["Incorrect Physics Model (Linear Motion)","Poor Rendering Performance (Judder/Low Frame Rate)","Contradiction Between Visuals and Data"],"verdict":"fail"},"raw_model_outputs":{"stage1_text":"Of course. As a strict animation and physics QA critic, I have analyzed the provided video of your \"SHM Spring Visualizer.\" The application's subtitle, \"Intentionally poor physics and UX,\" is accurate. Below is a comprehensive, technical critique of the animation and interaction behaviors.\n\n---\n\n### 1) Linear Motion Profile & Non-Sinusoidal Velocity\n**What happens**\nThe red mass moves back and forth with a visually constant velocity. It does not slow down as it approaches the endpoints, nor does it speed up as it passes through the central equilibrium point.\n\n**Why it looks wrong**\nThis motion is fundamentally incorrect for a spring-mass system. The physics of Simple Harmonic Motion (SHM) are governed by Hooke's Law (`F = -kx`), where the restoring force is proportional to the displacement (`x`). This dictates that acceleration is maximum at the endpoints (where the force is greatest) and zero at the equilibrium point. Consequently, the velocity profile must be sinusoidal (a cosine function if released from rest at maximum displacement), being zero at the endpoints and maximum at the center. The current implementation displays a \"triangle wave\" for position over time, which corresponds to a \"square wave\" for velocity. This feels robotic, weightless, and lacks any sense of inertia or dynamic force.\n\n**Fix**\nThe animation logic must be driven by a proper physics integration. Instead of updating position with a constant velocity (`x += v * dt`), you must calculate the state variables at each time step (`dt`).\n1.  Calculate force: `force = -k * position` (where `k` is the spring constant).\n2.  Calculate acceleration: `acceleration = force / mass`.\n3.  Update velocity: `velocity += acceleration * dt`.\n4.  Update position: `position += velocity * dt`.\nUsing a numerical integrator like Velocity Verlet or RK4 will yield a more stable and accurate simulation that produces the correct sinusoidal motion.\n\n### 2) Low-Frequency Update & Motion Judder\n**What happens**\nThe red mass does not travel smoothly. Instead, it visibly \"jumps\" or \"teleports\" in discrete steps along its path. The animation appears to be running at a very low and inconsistent frame rate.\n\n**Why it looks wrong**\nThis is a classic case of **frame-rate clipping** or judder, which severely degrades motion readability. The illusion of continuous motion is broken because the positional updates are too infrequent for the human eye to perceive as smooth. This suggests the animation loop is not synchronized with the display's refresh rate, likely relying on a slow `setInterval()` or `setTimeout()`. The large, discrete jumps in position indicate that the time delta (`dt`) between updates is too large.\n\n**Fix**\nDecouple the physics simulation loop from the rendering loop and use `requestAnimationFrame()` for all visual updates.\n1.  **Rendering:** The `requestAnimationFrame()` callback should be responsible only for drawing the state of the system (the ball's position, the spring's stretch) on the screen. This ensures rendering is synchronized with the monitor's refresh rate (typically 60Hz), eliminating judder.\n2.  **Physics:** Run the physics calculations on a separate, fixed time step (e.g., using `setInterval(physicsUpdate, 10)` for a 100Hz update rate). This ensures the simulation is deterministic and stable, regardless of rendering performance. For ultimate smoothness, the rendering loop can interpolate the object's position between the last two physics states.\n\n### 3) Instantaneous Velocity Inversion at Endpoints\n**What happens**\nWhen the mass reaches its maximum displacement (either fully stretched or fully compressed), its direction of motion reverses instantaneously. There is no visible deceleration to a stop or subsequent acceleration in the new direction.\n\n**Why it looks wrong**\nThis is a form of **corner glitching** applied to a 1D motion path. An object with mass cannot change its velocity instantaneously, as this would require infinite acceleration and thus an infinite force, violating Newton's laws of motion. This abrupt \"snap\" at the turning points is the most jarring visual artifact of the linear motion model. It completely removes the characteristic \"hang time\" where the object momentarily pauses before changing direction, which is crucial for believable physics.\n\n**Fix**\nThis issue is a direct symptom of the flawed model described in Problem #1. Implementing a proper force-based physics simulation will inherently solve this. As the mass approaches an endpoint, the restoring force will cause it to decelerate smoothly to a velocity of zero. The force will then continue to act on the mass, accelerating it smoothly in the opposite direction.\n\n### 4) Data-Visualization Mismatch\n**What happens**\nThe numerical readouts for Kinetic Energy (KE) and Potential Energy (PE) correctly show a sinusoidal transfer of energy, consistent with proper SHM. The PE is maximum when KE is zero (at the endpoints), and vice-versa (at the equilibrium point). However, the visual animation of the mass does not reflect this; it moves at a constant speed.\n\n**Why it looks wrong**\nThe UI presents two conflicting sources of information. The data *tells* the user that the system is behaving correctly according to SHM principles, but the animation *shows* a completely different, physically incorrect motion. This breaks the user's trust in the simulation. It implies that either the animation logic is disconnected from the physics engine driving the data, or the data itself is being \"faked\" with a simple sine/cosine function rather than being derived from the system's actual state.\n\n**Fix**\nEnsure a single source of truth for the system's state. The same `position` and `velocity` variables calculated in the physics loop (as per the fix for Problem #1) must be used for two purposes:\n1.  To calculate the KE (`0.5 * m * v^2`) and PE (`0.5 * k * x^2`) for the numerical display.\n2.  To directly determine the pixel coordinates of the red mass on the screen for rendering.\nThis will guarantee that the visual representation is a perfect match for the underlying data.","stage2_text":"```json\n{\n  \"overall_severity\": 10,\n  \"severity_reasoning\": \"The application fails on every fundamental level. The core physics model is incorrect (linear instead of sinusoidal), the animation rendering is severely degraded by low-frequency updates causing judder, and the visual representation directly contradicts the numerical data, completely undermining the purpose of the visualizer.\",\n  \"top_risks\": [\n    \"Incorrect Physics Model (Linear Motion)\",\n    \"Poor Rendering Performance (Judder/Low Frame Rate)\",\n    \"Contradiction Between Visuals and Data\"\n  ],\n  \"verdict\": \"fail\"\n}\n```","stage3_text":"```json\n{\n  \"verdict\": \"fail\",\n  \"overall_severity\": 10,\n  \"summary\": \"The application fundamentally fails as a physics visualizer. The core animation logic implements a linear motion profile instead of the required sinusoidal Simple Harmonic Motion, resulting in a physically impossible and robotic movement. This is compounded by severe animation judder due to a low-frequency update loop. Critically, the visual representation of the mass's motion directly contradicts the numerical data for kinetic and potential energy, completely undermining the tool's purpose and credibility.\",\n  \"defects\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"incorrect_physics_model\",\n      \"severity_0_10\": 10,\n      \"description\": \"The mass moves with a constant linear velocity, failing to slow down as it approaches the endpoints and speed up as it passes through equilibrium. This is fundamentally incorrect for a spring-mass system, which should exhibit sinusoidal velocity and acceleration based on Hooke's Law. The current motion feels weightless and lacks any sense of inertia or dynamic force.\",\n      \"evidence\": \"Throughout the video, the red mass travels back and forth at a visually constant speed. Its direction change at the endpoints is instantaneous.\",\n      \"recommendation\": \"Replace the current position update logic with a proper physics integration. At each time step (`dt`), calculate force (`F = -kx`), then acceleration (`a = F/m`), then update velocity (`v += a * dt`), and finally update position (`x += v * dt`). Using a numerical integrator like Velocity Verlet will produce the correct sinusoidal motion.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"data_visualization_mismatch\",\n      \"severity_0_10\": 10,\n      \"description\": \"The numerical readouts for Kinetic Energy (KE) and Potential Energy (PE) correctly show a sinusoidal transfer of energy consistent with proper SHM. However, the visual animation of the mass moves at a constant speed, which is a completely different and physically incorrect motion model. The UI presents two conflicting sources of information, breaking the user's trust.\",\n      \"evidence\": \"The numerical displays for KE and PE cycle smoothly between their maximum and minimum values, while the red mass on screen moves at a constant velocity.\",\n      \"recommendation\": \"Establish a single source of truth for the system's state. The same `position` and `velocity` variables calculated in the core physics loop must be used to both (1) render the position of the mass on screen and (2) calculate the KE (`0.5*m*v^2`) and PE (`0.5*k*x^2`) for the numerical display.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"instantaneous_velocity_inversion\",\n      \"severity_0_10\": 9,\n      \"description\": \"At the moment the mass reaches its maximum displacement, its velocity reverses instantaneously. An object with mass cannot change velocity without acceleration over time; this behavior requires infinite force and is physically impossible. This abrupt 'snap' is a jarring artifact that removes the characteristic 'hang time' of an oscillating object.\",\n      \"evidence\": \"At both the left and right turning points, the mass does not decelerate to a stop. It maintains full speed until the last frame and appears in the next frame moving at full speed in the opposite direction.\",\n      \"recommendation\": \"This issue is a direct symptom of the incorrect physics model. Implementing the recommended force-based physics simulation will inherently solve this. The restoring force will naturally cause the mass to decelerate smoothly to a velocity of zero at the endpoints before accelerating it in the opposite direction.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"animation_judder\",\n      \"severity_0_10\": 8,\n      \"description\": \"The motion of the mass is not smooth, exhibiting severe judder. The mass visibly 'jumps' or 'teleports' in discrete steps rather than traveling smoothly. This indicates that the animation is running at a very low and/or inconsistent frame rate, likely due to an improper update loop (e.g., slow `setInterval`). This breaks the illusion of continuous motion and degrades readability.\",\n      \"evidence\": \"The red mass does not move smoothly across the screen. Its movement is a series of discrete, visible jumps from one position to the next.\",\n      \"recommendation\": \"Decouple the physics simulation from the rendering loop. Use `requestAnimationFrame()` for all visual updates to synchronize drawing with the monitor's refresh rate, which will eliminate judder. The physics calculations should be run on a separate, fixed time step for stability and determinism.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"strengths\": [],\n  \"recommendations\": [\n    \"Overhaul the core logic to use a proper physics-based simulation (e.g., Velocity Verlet integrator) derived from Hooke's Law to accurately model Simple Harmonic Motion.\",\n    \"Refactor the rendering loop to use `requestAnimationFrame()` to ensure smooth, judder-free animation synchronized with the display's refresh rate.\",\n    \"Unify the application's state management so that the visual animation and the numerical data displays are both driven by the same underlying physics variables, ensuring consistency.\"\n  ],\n  \"score_breakdown\": {\n    \"physics_consistency\": 0,\n    \"collision_stability\": 0,\n    \"motion_readability\": 1,\n    \"temporal_smoothness\": 0\n  }\n}\n```"},"raw_model_diagnostics":{"stage1":{"ok":true,"status_code":200},"stage2":{"ok":true,"status_code":200},"stage3":{"ok":true,"status_code":200}}},"score_breakdown":{"physics_consistency":0,"collision_stability":0,"motion_readability":1,"temporal_smoothness":0}},"final_verdict":"fail","escalated":true,"severity_threshold":8,"pass_condition":"execution.status == pass AND critique.overall_severity <= 8.0"}}
